<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,1897,2030]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1897,1922]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Description.</emphasis>
Gonapophyses IX curvilinear, average length 1550.33 µm, width 86.90 µm, bearing 13 lobed teeth; apical third of apex carinate; apex porrect; small, sharp teeth on ventral surface of apex; ventral membranous sheath on distal third, small dorsal protuberance anterior to teeth (
<figureCitation box="[939,1032,1969,1994]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1958,1980]" captionTargetBox="[160,1426,305,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[160,1426,305,1916]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Lateral view of gonapophysis XI (apex of gonapophysis in inset) for A) Neopunana caribbensis (Neopunanini); B) Pentasteira albifrons (Platysystatini); C) Tetrasteira vulgaris (Tetrasteirini)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2588823/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
); space within carination of apex, smooth, with three pits; diagonal sculpturing on shaft (
<figureCitation box="[763,851,2005,2030]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1958,1980]" captionTargetBox="[160,1426,305,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[160,1426,305,1916]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Lateral view of gonapophysis XI (apex of gonapophysis in inset) for A) Neopunana caribbensis (Neopunanini); B) Pentasteira albifrons (Platysystatini); C) Tetrasteira vulgaris (Tetrasteirini)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2588823/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,248]" pageId="13" pageNumber="150">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,152,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="150">Notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emeljanov" authorityYear="1995" box="[282,433,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="150" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platysystatini">Platysystatini</taxonomicName>
includes five species in four genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Barringer, L. E. &amp; Bartlett, C. R." box="[866,1166,151,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="150" pagination="7 - 39" refId="ref11530" refString="Barringer, L. E. &amp; Bartlett, C. R. (2011) A review of New World Asiracinae (Hemiptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Delphacidae) with five new taxa. Cicadina, 12, 7 - 39." type="journal article" year="2011">Barringer &amp; Bartlett 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Asche, M. &amp; Webb, M. D." box="[1180,1425,151,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="150" pagination="163 - 169" refId="ref11209" refString="Asche, M. &amp; Webb, M. D. (2013) A remarkable new asiracine delphacid planthopper from Ecuador (Hemiptera, Fulgoroidea, Delphacidae). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift, 60 (2), 163 - 169. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / mmnd. 201300022" type="journal article" year="2013">Asche &amp; Webb 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The tribe is restricted to South America, where it evidently occurs in the rainforest canopy (
<bibRefCitation author="Barringer, L. E. &amp; Bartlett, C. R." pageId="13" pageNumber="150" pagination="7 - 39" refId="ref11530" refString="Barringer, L. E. &amp; Bartlett, C. R. (2011) A review of New World Asiracinae (Hemiptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Delphacidae) with five new taxa. Cicadina, 12, 7 - 39." type="journal article" year="2011">Barringer &amp; Bartlett 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Plant associations are unknown for the tribe, but possibly on canopy epiphytes.
</paragraph>
